Layout Detection – Simple Explanation

This component is responsible for identifying what type of insurance document a PDF is, such as:
	•	ACORD form
	•	Schedule of Values (SOV)
	•	Loss Run
	•	Inspection Report
	•	Property Detailed Report
	•	Submission Document

The system performs this in three main stages.

⸻

1. Download the Document

The API receives a Blob URL of a PDF document.

Example:

https://storage.blob.core.windows.net/container/file.pdf

The system:
	1.	Extracts the container name and file path from the URL.
	2.	Connects to Azure Blob Storage.
	3.	Downloads the PDF file.
	4.	Saves it locally inside an input folder.

At this point we now have the actual PDF file available locally.

⸻

2. Extract Document Content (Layout + Text)

Once the PDF is downloaded, the system sends it to Azure Form Recognizer using the prebuilt-layout model.

This model analyzes the structure of the document and extracts:
	•	Lines of text
	•	Layout information
	•	Tables (if present)

From the result we collect:

Extracted Text

All lines from all pages are combined into one large text string.

Example:

Producer: ABC Insurance Brokers
Insured: XYZ Manufacturing
Policy Number: 12345
Location: Building 1
Value: $5,000,000

Extracted Tables

If tables exist, they are collected separately.

Example table:

Location | Building | Value
1        | A        | 500000
2        | B        | 200000

The extracted information is stored as:

{
  "text": "...all extracted text...",
  "tables": [...]
}

⚠️ Important:

Currently only the text is used for classification.

Even though tables are extracted, they are not used by the classifier yet.

⸻

3. Classify the Document Type using LLM

The extracted text is sent to Azure OpenAI with a prompt that explains the possible document types.

The prompt tells the model to classify the document into exactly one category:

ACORD
SOV
LOSS_RUN
INSPECTION_REPORT
Property_Detailed_Report
Submission_Document

The model reads the first portion of the document text and determines which type it most closely matches.

Examples:

Example 1

Document contains:

ACORD 125
Producer
Insured
Certificate Holder
Policy Number

Model output:

ACORD


⸻

Example 2

Document contains:

Schedule of Values
Location | Building | Value
1 | Main Plant | 5000000

Model output:

SOV


⸻

Example 3

Document contains:

Loss Run Report
Claim Number
Date of Loss
Paid Amount
Reserve

Model output:

LOSS_RUN


⸻

4. Return the Result

The final response returned by the API contains:

{
  "status": true,
  "layout_type": "SOV",
  "URL": "<input blob url>"
}

This means:
	•	The classification was successful
	•	The document type detected is SOV
	•	The result corresponds to the provided blob URL

The result is also saved locally as:

output/layout_classification_result.json


⸻

Important Current Limitation

Although the system extracts tables from the document, the classification model currently uses only the extracted text.

The table structure is not yet used for classification logic.

This means documents like Schedule of Values, which are heavily table-based, are still classified only based on text patterns rather than table structure.

⸻

Overall Flow (Simple)

1️⃣ Receive Blob URL of PDF
2️⃣ Download PDF from Azure Blob Storage
3️⃣ Send PDF to Azure Form Recognizer
4️⃣ Extract text and tables
5️⃣ Send text to Azure OpenAI
6️⃣ LLM classifies document type
7️⃣ Return the detected layout type

